climbs.name: Wisconsin Rapids
climbs.fa: Curt Fry L-R and R-L & lap - Jack Dixon

content.description: A classic Chandler traverse with polished foot holds, a few sharp crimps, pinches, and a hefty middle finger mono. The crux is right in the middle and it only has one true rest spot.. the end before the lap back (making it a V7) The most stout V5 at Chandler, for sure.
content.location: Coming down the main stairs you will see Huey Couldn't Make It traverse straight in front of you. Take that corridor to the right and the start of Wisconsin is around the corner.

content.description: Start on water-cut ledges and work your way up the tallest section of the formation. Mostly pinches and crimps, there are one or two jugs to get ahold of. Crux is a balance-y move about 8 feet off the ground, where you have to move your feet higher while holding onto small holds
content.protection: You can walk up to the top of the formation from the back. There's a boulder and a tree on top to sling if you're not bouldering over a pad.
content.location: On the formation between the crux wall and the little to nothing wall, on the side of the formation that shares a corridor with the little to nothing wall.

content.description: Start just under the short roof around head height. Work your way up with big moves to good holds. Good warm up."Layman 5.9+ - Just around the corner from Little to Nothing. Find a foot wide deep cleft. To the left is a two foot roof at shoulder level. Ascend to the conspicuous jugs directly above and pull over the top." - Tulsa Rocks '90Other guidebooks call this a V0.
content.location: On the other side of the corner from Got Milk, before Wisconsin Rapids.

content.description: The crux is at the end (north east corner)
content.location: Starts on the south east corner and traverses the east face to Got Milk on the North east corner.  From the stairs, you run right into the start.

content.description: Crux is in the middle / low.  Great problem.  Sometimes has cobwebs on it.  Best to climb when dry.
content.location: Corner route on north east corner of Little to Nothing Wall.  This starts on the north side, not the east side.  Walk off.

content.description: Follow the Little to Nothing Wall north, turn left around the corner, (facing west now ) and walk along the cliffspan past several vertical cracks, until you get to the last tall arete. Big Buddha climbs left of the arete up "Happy Buddha" v4, and then tops out up and left instead of dropping off/downclimbing at the decent horizontal downpull hold 12 or so feet up. It adds another 12? feet of V1/ V2 or so movements. Anything on, or around the arete is off if I remember correctly. Found out about the route because of Brian Threlkeld (BT) and John Bagley. The traverse of Wisconsin rapids into Big Buddha would be crazy, and you could add in the Huey traverse as well.
content.location: The west side of the Little to Nothing cliffspan, before you get to the last major arete.

content.description: Always shaded.  This wall sees much less traffic then the ones further east.  It is only a 1 minute walk, but people just seem to shy away from it.  It can ooze some slime after rain for a while and there is more dirt / mud around it, which is probably why it sees less traffic.  It also hosts more difficult bouldering.  The traverses are excellent.
